				<h2><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111121233516/http://www.worldstallestwatersphere.com/?p=274" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Emmy Award Winning">Emmy Award Winning</a></h2>
				<small>April 22nd, 2010 <!-- by Spheroid --></small>
				
				<div class="entry">
					<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111121233516/http://www.worldstallestwatersphere.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/emmysphere2.jpg"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20111121233516im_/http://www.worldstallestwatersphere.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/emmysphere2-197x320.jpg" alt="Emmy Visits the WTWS" title="Emmy Visits the WTWS" width="197" height="320" class="alignright size-medium wp-image-275"/></a>Congratulations go to Brian Donohue for his work on the <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111121233516/http://www.nj.com/ledgerlive/">Star Ledger Live</a> site and all its interesting stories. The World&#8217;s Tallest Water Sphere site was interviewed for a segment back in <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111121233516/http://www.worldstallestwatersphere.com/?p=114">January of 2009</a>.</p>
<p>Brian Donohue has won an Emmy award for his work in interactive media. With a love for the World&#8217;s Tallest Water Sphere, New Jersey, and all it&#8217;s weirdness, what else could be done but to photograph the Emmy alongside the WTWS. We like the look! If ever there were structural problems, what else would be a better proposal than to have a giant, golden, art deco, statue prop the giant sphere?<br/>
<br clear="left"/></p>
